WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:17.130 --> 00:00:19.750
&gt;&gt; Sue Vita: Good
evening, everyone.

00:00:19.750 --> 00:00:22.140
Thank you for coming tonight.

00:00:22.140 --> 00:00:25.010
My name is Susan Vita,
and I'm the Chief

00:00:25.010 --> 00:00:28.370
of the Music Division
here at the Library.

00:00:28.370 --> 00:00:33.470
It is my pleasure to welcome
you tonight to the latest

00:00:33.470 --> 00:00:36.730
in our ongoing collaborative
lecture series

00:00:36.730 --> 00:00:39.900
with the American
Musicological Society.

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:42.560
This series has been
going strong

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:45.930
since the inaugural
lecture by Judith Tick

00:00:45.930 --> 00:00:51.170
on Ruth Crawford Seeger
probably 10 years ago.

00:00:51.170 --> 00:00:53.710
And we are pleased to
co-sponsor the series

00:00:53.710 --> 00:00:56.240
which highlights
research that was done

00:00:56.240 --> 00:01:00.770
in the Music Division
either in-house or online.

00:01:00.770 --> 00:01:05.840
Tonight's lecture by Dr. Daniel
Callahan will explore the

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:08.250
physicality of Leonard
Bernstein's

00:01:08.250 --> 00:01:10.400
conflicting practices.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:12.950
Sorry, conducting practices.

00:01:12.950 --> 00:01:14.840
Probably both.

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:20.110
And fits right in with
the worldwide celebration

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:23.400
of Bernstein's centenary
this year.

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:31.010
Somebody told me that there are
20 events celebrating Bernstein

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:37.860
this week, so I'm glad that
you all chose ours, and --

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:39.160
as you know, the Library

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:42.680
of Congress holds the
Leonard Bernstein Collection

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:47.240
which contains 400,000 items.

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:50.500
This AMS Lecture is part
of a week-long series

00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:54.090
of events looking at
many different aspects

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:56.560
of the American icon.

00:01:56.560 --> 00:02:00.540
We hope that you will join us
for our other events as well

00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:05.190
which include a screening of <i>On
the Waterfront, </i>on Thursday,

00:02:05.190 --> 00:02:09.220
a concert on Friday of known

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:13.650
and unknow Bernstein songs
featuring Michael Barrett

00:02:13.650 --> 00:02:17.640
and a fantastic team
of young singers.

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:20.280
I'm just really looking
forward to that,

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:25.270
and another all-day
affair on Saturday,

00:02:25.270 --> 00:02:29.700
which is not the Royal
Wedding [laughter],

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:33.190
in which we will have six
speakers and performers talking

00:02:33.190 --> 00:02:35.160
about all things Bernstein.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:38.210
We will also have a
selection of the treasures

00:02:38.210 --> 00:02:40.070
from the Bernstein
collection that will be

00:02:40.070 --> 00:02:45.800
on display all day long, and
we hope to see you there.

00:02:45.800 --> 00:02:48.180
While there is nothing
like being there in person,

00:02:48.180 --> 00:02:50.500
one great thing about
the AMS Library

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:54.390
of Congress partnership is
that we record the lectures

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:59.060
for future webcasts on the
Library's website and YouTube.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:01.750
And the lectures of the
talented scholars selected

00:03:01.750 --> 00:03:07.390
for the series are available for
all to enjoy around the world.

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:09.370
Before Dr. Callahan speaks,

00:03:09.370 --> 00:03:12.120
I'd like to introduce
Martha Feldman,

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:16.280
the Mable Green Meyers Professor
of Music and the Humanities

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:21.170
at the College -- in the College
at the University of Chicago.

00:03:21.170 --> 00:03:23.210
Professor Feldman
is the President

00:03:23.210 --> 00:03:25.420
of the American Musicological
Society

00:03:25.420 --> 00:03:29.840
and will be offering her
greetings from the Society.

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:32.840
So thank you all again for
joining us this evening

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:37.510
and please join me in
welcoming Professor Feldman.

00:03:37.510 --> 00:03:43.040
[ Applause ]

00:03:43.040 --> 00:03:47.360
&gt;&gt; Martha Feldman: It's really
an enormous pleasure to be here

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:52.580
and to be able to introduce an
AMS Library of Congress Lecturer

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:56.130
at this amazing great
institution

00:03:56.130 --> 00:04:00.310
where I actually carried
out dissertation research

00:04:00.310 --> 00:04:07.800
as an avid, very zealous PhD
student quite some time ago,

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:09.100
decades ago.

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:11.350
I won't say how many.

00:04:11.350 --> 00:04:14.150
Like many AMS members,
I've returned

00:04:14.150 --> 00:04:19.630
to the Library's collections
in music and have worked

00:04:19.630 --> 00:04:24.720
in other areas of the Library
many times over the years

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:30.880
in person, by correspondence,
and now digitally as well.

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:33.820
So it's very, very rewarding
to be able to participate

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:38.680
in this collaboration during
my tenure as AMS President.

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:42.270
I want to thank very sincerely
the staff who have helped

00:04:42.270 --> 00:04:46.190
with this -- David Plyler,
Kate Miller, Ben Walsh,

00:04:46.190 --> 00:04:49.560
and, of course Susan Vita.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:54.220
And with that, let me just say
that I'm particularly happy

00:04:54.220 --> 00:04:56.840
and honored to introduce
tonight's speaker,

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:02.610
Professor Daniel Callahan, a
valued colleague in musicology

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:05.600
and a dear friend as well.

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:10.830
Daniel earned his BA at
NYU and his MA, M.Phil.,

00:05:10.830 --> 00:05:17.450
and PhD at Columbia University,
the last of those in 2012.

00:05:17.450 --> 00:05:22.140
Since 2014, Daniel has been
Assistant Professor of Music

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:25.640
at Boston College where he
teaches courses that range

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:31.100
from Aesthetics, Empathy, and
Ethics to Modernism in Dance.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:34.770
Before that, he was the Mellon
Postdoctoral Fellow and Lecturer

00:05:34.770 --> 00:05:38.560
in Music in the Humanities
at the University of Chicago,

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:42.420
a position into which I was
lucky enough to have hired him

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:45.780
in 2012 when chairing
my department,

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:49.920
that's before we were
friends, and where he taught

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:53.810
for two years Undergraduate
and Graduate Courses.

00:05:53.810 --> 00:05:58.390
He taught wonderful
courses on music video,

00:05:58.390 --> 00:06:02.660
Soundies to YouTube,
and Choreomusicalities,

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:07.460
and collaborations
between different composers

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:09.830
and choreographers, and things
that none of us were doing

00:06:09.830 --> 00:06:14.230
and none of us had, in
some cases, even heard of.

00:06:14.230 --> 00:06:16.920
A cellist and dancer himself,

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:19.410
Daniel has given an
extraordinary number

00:06:19.410 --> 00:06:23.610
of professional papers on topics
that stretch from Bernstein,

00:06:23.610 --> 00:06:26.810
Copeland, and John Cage, to
Mullermae [assumed spelling],

00:06:26.810 --> 00:06:31.010
1930's cartoons, Maersk
Cunningham, Nijinsky, Ted Shawn

00:06:31.010 --> 00:06:33.980
and his Men Dancers,
and in approaches

00:06:33.980 --> 00:06:36.710
that suture together the
concerns of music, dance,

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:42.130
and image with those of
gay aesthetics and desire.

00:06:42.130 --> 00:06:45.670
Daniel Callahan is the recipient
of many grants, fellowships,

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:48.510
and awards in addition
to the Mellon Postdoc

00:06:48.510 --> 00:06:50.560
that I mentioned earlier.

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:53.880
He's won a Whiting Dissertation
Completion Fellowship,

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:56.390
the Selma Jeanne Cohen
Award from the Society

00:06:56.390 --> 00:06:59.430
of Dance History
Scholars, and various awards

00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:03.090
from Boston College,
Columbia, and AMS.

00:07:03.090 --> 00:07:04.980
This summer we'll
see the publication

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:08.380
of Daniel's ambitious and
much anticipated article

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:12.540
for the <i>Journal of the American
Musicological Society </i>entitled,

00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:16.390
"The Gay Divorce of Music
and Dance, Choreomusicality,

00:07:16.390 --> 00:07:20.650
and the Early Works
of Cage-Cunningham,"

00:07:20.650 --> 00:07:23.790
which adduces new archival
and performative evidence

00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:28.330
for the early collaborations of
John Cage and Merce Cunningham,

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:31.660
to argue that music and
dance were not divided

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:35.370
in their early years but
were interrelated intimately,

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:39.830
especially through gay critiques
of heterosexual marriage.

00:07:39.830 --> 00:07:41.950
Given that Daniel has
established himself

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:46.060
in public presentations as an
intellect to be reckoned with,

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:48.370
there's reason for great
excitement about his book

00:07:48.370 --> 00:07:52.580
in progress, <i>The Dancer From
the Music, Choreomusicalities</i>

00:07:52.580 --> 00:07:56.360
<i>in American Modern Dance </i>which
is bound to set American music

00:07:56.360 --> 00:07:59.140
and dance studies
on a new course.

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:02.600
Please join me in welcoming
Professor Daniel Callahan

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:06.570
in his AMS Library of
Congress lecture entitled

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:09.510
"Bernstein Conducting Himself."

00:08:09.510 --> 00:08:18.060
[ Applause ]

